n problem until now. The limit of the system associated with differential games with finitely many players is described by the so-called master equation, a nonlocal transport equation in the space of measures. After defining a suitable notion of differentiability in the space of measures, the authors provide a complete self-contained analysis of the master equation. Their analysis includes the case of common noise problems in which all the players are affected by a common Brownian motion. They then go on to explain how to use the master equation to prove the mean field limit.This groundbreaking book presents two important new results in mean field games that contribute to a unified theoretical framework for this exciting and fast-developing area of mathematics.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 31. Jan 2022) 0aConvergence. 0aMean field theory. 7aMATHEMATICS / Game Theory.2bisacsh  aA priori estimate.  aApproximation.  aBellman equation.  aBoltzmann equation.  aBoundary value problem.  aC0.  aChain rule.  aCompact space.  aComputation.  aConditional probability distribution.  aContinuous function.  aConvergence problem.  aConvex set.  aCooperative game.  aCorollary.  aDecision-making.  aDerivative.  aDeterministic system.  aDifferentiable function.  aDirectional derivative.  aDiscrete time and continuous time.  aDiscretization.  aDynamic programming.  aEmergence.  aEmpirical distribution function.  aEquation.  aEstimation.  aEuclidean space.  aFolk theorem (game theory).  aFolk theorem.  aHeat equation.  aHermitian adjoint.  aImplementation.  aInitial condition.  aInteger.  aLarge numbers.  aLinearization.  aLipschitz continuity.  aLp space.  aMacroeconomic model.  aMarkov process.  aMartingale (probability theory).  aMaster equation.  aMathematic